  "description": "Experimental gas-phase fundamental vibrational frequencies for small molecules, with mode symmetry and description. Curated from NIST CCCBDB experimental section (fetched 2026-07-22), which tabulates values from Shimanouchi 'Tables of Molecular Vibrational Frequencies' (NSRDS-NBS 39, 1972) and other primary spectroscopy. Every molecule here was cross-checked against both CCCBDB and the Shimanouchi compilation.",
  "units": {
    "frequency": "cm^-1",
    "type": "experimental fundamental (anharmonic, observed band origin) frequencies"
  },
  "retrieved": "2026-07-22",
  "caveat": "These are EXPERIMENTAL FUNDAMENTAL (anharmonic) frequencies. A harmonic normal-mode calculation (the default from an ML potential Hessian or ab initio second derivatives) yields HARMONIC frequencies omega_e, which are systematically HIGHER than observed fundamentals nu (typically by 3-6 percent for X-H stretches). Do NOT compare harmonic omega directly to these fundamentals. To compare like-with-like, either (a) apply a published harmonic-to-fundamental scaling factor appropriate to the method (see CCCBDB vibscale tables), or (b) compute anharmonic frequencies (e.g. VPT2) and compare to these. Fermi resonances (notably CO2 nu1/2nu2) further complicate direct comparison; the CO2 nu1 value 1333 is the deperturbed fundamental, observed as a Fermi dyad at ~1388/1285. See README.md.",
  "primary_sources": [
